### Inheritance in Kotlin

Kotlin supports single inheritance. All classes are `final` by default and must be marked `open` to be extended.

---

### Open Class

Classes are `final` by default. Use the `open` keyword to allow inheritance.

```kotlin
open class Animal(val name: String) {
    open fun makeSound() {
        println("Animal makes a sound")
    }
}
```

---

### Inheriting from a Class

Use a colon (`:`) and call the parent constructor.

```kotlin
open class Animal(val name: String)

class Dog(name: String) : Animal(name) {
    fun wagTail() {
        println("$name wags tail")
    }
}
```

---

### Calling Superclass Methods and Properties

```kotlin
open class Animal(val name: String) {
    open fun makeSound() = println("$name makes a sound")
}

class Dog(name: String) : Animal(name) {
    override fun makeSound() {
        super.makeSound()  // Call parent implementation
        println("$name barks")
    }
}
```

---

### Inheritance Hierarchy

```kotlin
open class LivingBeing
open class Animal : LivingBeing()
open class Mammal : Animal()
class Dog : Mammal()
```

---

### Abstract Classes

Abstract classes are implicitly `open` and cannot be instantiated.

```kotlin
abstract class Shape {
    abstract fun area(): Double

    fun description(): String {
        return "Shape with area ${area()}"
    }
}

class Circle(val radius: Double) : Shape() {
    override fun area() = Math.PI * radius * radius
}
```

---

### Preventing Inheritance

Mark a class or method as `final` to stop further overriding.

```kotlin
open class Parent {
    open fun canOverride() {}
    final fun cannotOverride() {}
}

class Child : Parent() {
    override fun canOverride() {}
    // override fun cannotOverride() {}  // Error
}
```

> **Key Point:** All classes and methods are `final` by default. This follows the principle of favoring composition over inheritance and makes code more predictable.

codeExample:
open class Vehicle(val brand: String, val year: Int) {
    open fun start() = println("$brand vehicle starting")
    open fun info() = "$brand ($year)"
}

class Car(brand: String, year: Int, val model: String) : Vehicle(brand, year) {
    override fun start() {
        println("$brand $model engine starting")
    }

    override fun info() = "${super.info()} $model"
}

fun main() {
    val car = Car("Toyota", 2020, "Camry")
    car.start()
    println(car.info())
}
